        <h1>
          <div class="tweet-btn">
            <iframe allowtransparency="true" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" src="/a/1314118012/iframe/tweet_button.html#en#en" style="height: 20px; width: 57px; "></iframe>
          </div>
          Absolute Radio <small>@AbsoluteRadio</small>
        </h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Absolute Radio increases online listening by seven percent with Twitter
        </p><img alt="Absolute Radio" class="bordered" src="/a/1314118012/images/business/case-studies/absoluteradio-screenshot.png">
        <h3>
          The Challenge
        </h3>
        <p>
          @AbsoluteRadio launched an integrated marketing campaign called “Faces for Radio” to better highlight the variety of music the UK radio station plays. Across search, display and outdoor advertisements, the campaign focused on the musical artists featured on air as well as the station’s well-known presenters like Frank Skinner. But the UK brand wanted to bolster the campaign with one critical component: a real-time platform that would amplify the live radio experience and keep their tech-savvy listeners engaged.
        </p>       
        <h3>
          The Solution
        </h3>
        <img alt="Absolute Radio" class="bordered" src="/a/1314118012/images/business/case-studies/absoluteradio-screenshot-1.png">
        <p>
          The brand chose to own the conversation around a popular hashtag that Twitter users include whenever they tweet about music they are listening to. Centered around its Promoted Trend (#nowplaying), @AbsoluteRadio hosted a Twitter exclusive contest and gave away £250 every hour for 24 hours. To enter to win, listeners had to tweet the name of the artist that was playing on air to @AbsoluteRadio and include the hashtag #nowplaying. @AbsoluteRadio believed users would be more likely to engage with a hashtag that they were already accustomed to using organically.
        </p>
        <p>
          “‘Now playing’ was language we were already featuring throughout the display and outdoor ads and words we were bidding on in search,” said Laura Tannenbaum, Brand Marketing Manager at Absolute Radio. “#nowplaying also gave us the ability to piggy-back on social conversations already happening on Twitter and surface our brand and message to the top.”
        </p>
        <p>
          @AbsoluteRadio closely tied the Promoted Trend into the on-air experience to amplify reach and build excitement. In the days leading up to the Promoted Trend, the station’s presenters heavily promoted the contest on air and @AbsoluteRadio used Promoted Tweets to seed the hashtag. On the Promoted Trend day, the on-air talent also turned to Twitter to nurture a dialogue with listeners in real time. They used Tweets in the #nowplaying hashtag stream to give shoutouts, answer questions and spark conversations about songs and artists.
        </p>
        <p>
          “The campaign gave us the ability to bring together the immediateness of radio with immediateness of Twitter to create a campaign that was powerful, flexible and real-time,” says Tannenbaum.
        </p>
        <p>
          Throughout the day of the Promoted Trend, @AbsoluteRadio updated the related Promoted Tweets so that users clicking on the Promoted Trend would always see the most relevant messages. The station created an increasing sense of urgency as every hour passed during the 24 hours of the contest. @AbsoluteRadio also optimized Promoted Tweets in search based on what artists were playing on the radio throughout the 24-hour period to fuel discovery and spark social conversation.
        </p>  
        <h3>
          The Results
        </h3>
        <p>
          During the Promoted Trend day, conversations around @AbsoluteRadio spiked with 76,000 mentions reaching 23 million people on Twitter. Twitter users sent more than 100,000 Tweets with the #nowplaying hashtag. The station also saw a significant increase in online listening of seven percent on the day of the Twitter contest.
        </p>
        <p>
          “The campaign on Twitter was successful in every single metric, offering us the immediacy we wanted, at the scale we needed,” says Tannenbaum. “On Twitter, our listeners became brand ambassadors, sharing live updates of our playlist with all their followers.”
        </p>
        <p>
          The Promoted Trend also had an unexpected but powerful effect on organic trends. On the day of the Promoted Trend, 41 of the artists (including Primal Scream, Blur, The Killers and Spin Doctors) that @AbsoluteRadio played on the radio trended organically in the UK—a first on Twitter. Throughout the day, natural discovery fuelled the overall awareness and virality of the campaign as users on Twitter clicked to explore why certain bands were trending.
        </p>
        <p>
          “We were able to enhance the campaign on Twitter and on air in real time to address what users were talking about at every moment throughout the day,” says Tannenbaum. “Twitter gave us the crucial, real-time ability to have a two-way conversation that no other medium could have given us.”
        </p><br>
        <a class="btn btn-m btn-blue" href="../afer">Next Case Study →</a> <a class="btn btn-m btn-blue" href="/en/advertise/promoted-tweets">Skip to Promoted Tweets →</a>
      </div>
